 to this ancient heroine can be progressive or is bound to idealize the past, and why Antigone keeps entering the stage in times of political crisis and struggle in all corners of the world. Fanny Söderbäck has gathered classic work in this field alongside newly written pieces by some of the most important voices in contemporary feminist philosophy. The volume includes essays by Judith Butler, Adriana Cavarero, Tina Chanter, Luce Irigaray, and Julia Kristeva.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aAntigone (Greek mythology) in literature. 0aFeminism and literaturezGreece. 0aSex role in literature. 0aTragedy. 0aWomen in literature. 4aPhilosophy : Continental Philosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh1 aBernstein, J. M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aButler, Judith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCavarero, Adriana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChanter, Tina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEttinger, Bracha L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFradinger, Moira, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHolland, Catherine A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIrigaray, Luce, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKristeva, Julia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMader, Mary Beth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSjöholm, Cecilia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSoderback, Fanny, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSöderbäck, Fanny, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of 